@flexiarg process-coherence/author-the-missing-pattern
@title The Library Is Incomplete by Construction — Author What the Argument Needs
@sigils [✍/📚]
@keywords library gap, thin cascade, author patterns, incomplete by construction, warrant, real argument, transparency, R17
@audience anyone whose argument came back thin because the library lacked the vocabulary
@tone procedural
@style pattern

! conclusion: When a well-formed circumstance draws a thin argument (few or no relevant patterns), do not treat "what the existing library retrieves" as the warrant and move on — the library is INCOMPLETE BY CONSTRUCTION. Author real patterns from the built system's actual functionality, put them forward in the real argument, and let the argument's improvement justify them. Authoring is part of operating, not maintenance.

  + context: Retrieval-over-a-library systems quietly convert "the library
    has no vocabulary here" into "there is no argument here." The library
    was never complete; treating it as the fixed warrant makes its gaps
    invisible and permanent.

  + IF:
      A well-formed circumstance (the want and have are real and clearly
      stated) draws a thin or empty argument from the library.

  + HOWEVER:
      The temptation is to enrich the QUERY, lower the bar, or accept the
      thin argument — all of which paper over the actual fact: the
      library lacks the domain's patterns, because nobody has written
      them yet.

  + THEN:
      Author the missing patterns — from real, built, working practice
      (the system's actual functionality, real cases with real numbers as
      canonical instances), not from speculation. Ingest them through the
      standard pipeline (retrievable, eligible, fairly priced), then
      RE-RUN the argument and record before/after. The patterns are
      justified transparently: by the functionality they describe and the
      argument they improve.

  + BECAUSE:
      A pattern language grows at exactly the places arguments fail —
      that is the loop's structure-learning obligation (R17), and it only
      happens if gap-hit ⇒ authoring is the standing response. A library
      treated as fixed warrant converges to arguing only about its past.
      (Kin: [[proof-search/sorry-boundary-clustering]] found this way;
      [[process-coherence/is-this-even-a-problem]] — sometimes the gap IS
      the answer.)

  + canonical-instance:
      2026-07-05: M-diagramprover's well-formed sorry-grain ψ drew size 1,
      F −0.443 — the library had no proof-search vocabulary at all. The
      response was three authored patterns (proof-search/*) from the real
      prelim-corpus practice (39 partials, 489 problems), ingested via the
      seeds pipeline, with the re-run measured before/after. Operator
      doctrine, same day: "we've been using 'existing library patterns'
      as a warrant, but the library is incomplete by construction — author
      real patterns and put them forward in a real argument."
